|Q1]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2008 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|3R]]\n|bgcolor=ffebcd|[[2009 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|QF]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2010 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2011 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|3R]]\n|bgcolor=ffebcd|[[2012 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|QF]]\n|A\n|bgcolor=lime|[[2014 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|'''W''']]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2015 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|SF]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2016 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|3R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2017 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|3R]]\n|bgcolor=ffebcd|[[2018 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|QF]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2019 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|4R]]\n|\n|1 / 11\n|36\u201310\n|78%\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#efefef;\"\n|style=text-align:left|Win\u2013Loss\n|0\u20130\n|0\u20133\n|9\u20134\n|12\u20134\n|9\u20134\n|5\u20134\n|9\u20133\n|5\u20132\n|14\u20133\n|12\u20133\n|8\u20134\n|13\u20134\n|15\u20134\n|8\u20134\n|3\u20131\n|1 / 49\n|122\u201347\n|72%\n|}\n<small>''* \u010cili\u0107 withdrew before the second round match at the [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2013 Wimbledon]].</small>\n\n;<big>Finals: 3 (1 title, 2 runner-ups)</big>\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n\n|-\n!width=80|Result\n!width=50|Year\n!width=200|Tournament\n!width=50|Surface\n!width=200|Opponent\n!width=180|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner||[[2014 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2014]]||[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]||Hard||{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kei Nishikori]]||6\u20133, 6\u20133, 6\u20133\n|- style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A;\"|Runner-up||[[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2017]]||[[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]||Grass||{{flagicon|SUI}} [[Roger Federer]]||3\u20136, 1\u20136, 4\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n|bgcolor=ffa07a|Runner-up||[[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]]||[[Australian Open]]||Hard||{{flagicon|SUI}} [[Roger Federer]] ||2\u20136, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20135)</sup>, 3\u20136, 6\u20133, 1\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.marin-cilic.net/ Official website] {{in lang|en|hr|fr}}\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Davis Cup player}}\n* [http://marincilic.wordpress.com/ Website] about Marin \u010cili\u0107 {{in lang|en|fr}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090121175315/http://atpworldtour.com/5/en/deuce/january2009/cilic.asp ATP DEUCE Magazine: On the Rise... Marin \u010cili\u0107]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box \n| before = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Bob Bryan]] &<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Mike Bryan]]\n| after = {{flagicon|ROU}} [[Horia Tec\u0103u]]\n| title = [[ATP Arthur Ashe Humanitarian award|Arthur Ashe Humanitarian of the Year]]\n| years = [[2016 ATP World Tour|2016]]\n|}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{French Open boys' singles champions}}\n{{US Open men's singles champions}}\n{{ATP Masters Series tournament winners}}\n{{Top Croatian male tennis players}}\n{{Top ten Croatian male doubles tennis players}}\n{{Croatian Athlete of the Year (men)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cilic, Marin}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Croatian male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriates in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Croatian sportspeople in doping cases]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Croatian people of Bosnia and Herzegovina descent]]\n[[Category:French Open junior champions]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's singles]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of Croatia]]\n[[Category:People from Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:People from Monte Carlo]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:US Open (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:21st-century Croatian people]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in tennis]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in boys' singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Croatian tennis player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name= Marin \u010cili\u0107\n|image= Cilic WM18 (62) (43932286881).jpg\n|caption= \u010cili\u0107 at the [[2018 Wimbledon Championships]]\n|country= {{CRO}} \n|residence= [[Monte Carlo]], Monaco\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|9|28}}<ref name=\"atp-profile\">{{cite web |title=Marin Cilic |url=https://www.atptour.com/en/players/marin-cilic/c977/overview |website=ATP World Tour |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_place= [[Me\u0111ugorje]], [[SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]] \n|height={{height|m=1.98|precision=0}}\n|turnedpro= 2005\n|coach= [[Bob Brett]] (2004\u20132013)<br>[[Goran Ivani\u0161evi\u0107]] (2013\u20132016)<br>[[Jonas Bj\u00f6rkman]] (2016\u20132017)<br>Ivan Cinku\u0161 (2018\u2013present)\n|plays= Right-handed (two-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney= $27,864,286\n* <small>&nbsp;[[Open Era tennis records \u2013 men's singles#Prize money|10th&nbsp;all-time&nbsp;leader&nbsp;in&nbsp;earnings]]</small>\n|website= {{URL|marincilic.com}}\n|singlesrecord= {{tennis record|won=508|lost=275|details=in [[ATP Tour]] and [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n|singlestitles=18\n|highestsinglesranking= No. 3 (29 January 2018)\n|currentsinglesranking= No. 37 (9 March 2020<!-- - ALWAYS THE DATE WHEN THE PLAYER MOST RECENTLY OBTAINED THEIR CURRENT RANKING, DOES NOT NEED TO BE EDITED- -->)<ref>[https://www.atptour.com/en/rankings/singles?rankDate=2019-07-01&rankRange=0-100&countryCode=CRO]</ref>\n|AustralianOpenresult= F ([[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n|FrenchOpenresult= QF ([[2017 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2017]], [[2018 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n|Wimbledonresult= F ([[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2017]])\n|USOpenresult= '''W''' ([[2014 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2014]])\n|Othertournaments= yes\n|MastersCupresult= RR ([[2014 ATP World Tour Finals \u2013 Singles|2014]], [[2016 ATP World Tour Finals \u2013 Singles|2016]], [[2017 ATP Finals \u2013 Singles|2017]], [[2018 ATP Finals \u2013 Singles|2018]])\n|Olympicsresult= 3R ([[Tennis at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's singles|2016]])\n|doublesrecord= {{tennis record|won=79|lost=89|details=in [[ATP Tour]] and [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n|doublestitles= 0\n|highestdoublesranking= No. 49 (15 April 2013)\n|currentdoublesranking= No. 458 (9 March 2020)\n|Team= yes\n|DavisCupresult= '''W''' ([[2018 Davis Cup World Group|2018]])\n|updated= {{as of|2020|03|22|lc=y}}\n}}\n\n'''Marin \u010cili\u0107''' ({{IPA-hr|m\u00e2ri\u02d0n t\u0283\u01d0\u02d0lit\u0255|hr}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=e1xhXBc%3D|title=M\u0201r\u012bn|quote=M\u0201r\u012bn|website=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=f1pnXBM%3D&keyword=%C4%8Dila%C5%A1|title=\u010d\u00ecl\u0101\u0161|quote=\u010c\u00edli\u0107|website=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The pronunciation by Marin \u010cili\u0107 himself|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/-/media/player-names/57_marin-cilic_player-name-2014.mp3|publisher=ATP World Tour|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref> born 28 September 1988) is a Croatian professional [[tennis]] player. Over the course of his career, \u010cili\u0107 has won 18 [[ATP Tour]] singles titles, including a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] title at the [[2014 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2014 US Open]]. His career-high singles [[ATP Rankings|ranking]] is world No. 3, achieved on 28 January 2018. \u010cili\u0107 first came to international prominence by defeating world No. 2 [[Andy Murray]] in the fourth round of the [[2009 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2009 US Open]], and then reaching the semi-finals at the [[2010 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Australian Open]] a few months later. He was also runner-up at the [[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2017 Wimbledon Championships]] and the [[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018 Australian Open]], losing to [[Roger Federer]] both times. \u010cili\u0107 has reached at least quarterfinal in all four major tournaments, and has made it to at least that stage at 13 different Grand Slams. He is known for his fast serves and powerful ground-strokes.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 started to develop his career at a young age; his first steps of tennis started in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. His potential was discovered by local hometown coaches who saw him play and encouraged his move to [[Zagreb]] for further training.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/tennis/cilics-family-watching-and-hoping-20100127-mz18.html|title=Cilic's family watching and hoping|publisher=Theage.com.au|date=28 January 2010|accessdate=24 February 2010|location=Melbourne|first=Selma|last=Milovanovic}}</ref> He was soon befriended by his countryman to be [[Goran Ivani\u0161evi\u0107]], who introduced him to coach [[Bob Brett]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/tennis/the-australian-behind-the-rise-of-cilic-20100127-mz16.html|title=The Australian behind the rise of Cilic|publisher=Theage.com.au|date=28 January 2010|accessdate=24 February 2010|location=Melbourne}}</ref> \u010cili\u0107 turned professional in 2005,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Top-Players/Marin-Cilic.aspx |title=Marin Cilic Profile |publisher=Association of Tennis Professionals}}</ref> and ultimately hired Ivani\u0161evi\u0107 as his full-time coach in 2013. \u010cili\u0107 parted ways with Ivani\u0161evi\u0107 in late July 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MarinCilic/posts/1359372124092571|title=Marin Cilic \u2013 Timeline {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref> after advancing to the [[2015 Davis Cup]] semifinals.\n\n==Personal life==\nMarin \u010cili\u0107 was born in Krstine, [[Me\u0111ugorje]], a town in [[Herzegovina]] region of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] to [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Herzegovinian Croat]] parents. He was raised as a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |date=27 January 2010 |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/76601/marin-cilic-nisam-oklijevao-igrati-za-hrvatsku-i-vjerujem-u-gospino-ukazanje |accessdate=29 May 2010 |quote=Katolik sam, tako sam odgojen.(\"I am a Catholic, so I was raised\") |title=Marin \u010cili\u0107: Nisam oklijevao igrati za Hrvatsku i vjerujem u Gospino ukazanje |trans-title=Marin \u010cili\u0107: I did not hesitate to play for Croatia and I believe in appearance of Our Lady |language=Croatian |archivedate=24 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69OagUdKT?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/76601/marin-cilic-nisam-oklijevao-igrati-za-hrvatsku-i-vjerujem-u-gospino-ukazanje |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=eZadar|author2=Index|title=Cilic: I was born in Medjugorje, and I believe in miracles|publisher=eZadar|date=27 January 2010|url=http://www.ezadar.hr/clanak/cilic-roden-sam-u-medugorju-i-vjerujem-u-cuda|accessdate=29 May 2010|quote=...Katolik sam, tako su me odgojili otac i majka...(\"...I am a Catholic, so I was raised by my father and mother...\")|language=hr}}</ref> His father Zdenko was determined that his sons \u2013 Marin and older brothers Vinko and Goran \u2013 would have the opportunities he lacked in playing sports. When the first tennis courts in the town were built in 1991, Marin and his friends were among the first to play on them. At the recommendation of [[Goran Ivani\u0161evi\u0107]], in 2004, at the age of 15, \u010cili\u0107 moved to [[Sanremo|San Remo]], [[Italy]] to work with Ivani\u0161evi\u0107's former coach, [[Bob Brett]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australianopen.com/mobile/news/2010-01-26/201001261264489755843.html|title=Mobile Australian Open|publisher=Australianopen.com|date=26 January 2010|accessdate=24 February 2010}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He has a younger brother, Mile, who also plays tennis. On 28 April 2018, he married his long time girlfriend Kristina Milkovi\u0107. They have a son Baldo.\n\n==Tennis career==\n===2004\u201305: Junior circuit===\n\u010cili\u0107 began playing on the junior [[International Tennis Federation|ITF]] circuit in spring 2004. At the start he played on clay courts, winning the ''La Vie Junior Cup Villach'' in singles and the Dutch Junior Open in doubles. He then qualified for the [[2004 US Open (tennis)|2004 US Open]], where he lost in the second round to [[Sam Querrey]]. In 2005, he won the [[2005 French Open|French Open]] title in Boys' singles, beating [[Andy Murray]] in the semifinal<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/tennis/4608493.stm|work=BBC News|title=Murray loses in French semi-final|date=3 June 2005|accessdate=12 May 2010}}</ref> and [[Antal van der Duim]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatia.org/crown/articles/7816/1/E-MARIN-CILIC-JUNIOR-CHAMPION.html|work=Croatian World Network|title=MARIN CILIC JUNIOR CHAMPION|date=10 July 2005|accessdate=10 July 2005}}</ref> He finished 2005 ranked number two behind American [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]]. While on the junior circuit, he won six tournaments in singles and four in doubles with his Canadian partner, Greg Kates.\n\nBefore representing Croatia, he played for [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] as a junior with partner Zachary Rosen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://san.ba/index.php?id=10145 |title=SAN Dnevne novine |publisher=San.ba |date=29 January 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203032512/http://www.san.ba/index.php?id=10145 |archivedate=3 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132007: ATP Tour===\nIn 2004, \u010cili\u0107 played one [[ITF Men's Circuit|Futures]] event (Croatia F1), at which he reached the second round; he finished the year tied at No. 1463 on the rankings of the [[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP Tour). He played seven Futures tournaments in 2005, winning one, the Croatia F3 event; two [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] tournaments, in [[Zagreb]] and [[Geneva]]; and one ATP International Series tournament, the [[Croatia Open]], where he lost in the opening round. He finished the year ranked No. 587.\n\nIn 2006, he played three Futures, winning the Croatia F1 and Croatia F2 events. He also played in nine challengers, nine International Series events (reaching the semifinals at [[Swiss Open (tennis)|Gstaad]]),<ref name=fox101>{{cite web|title=Zverev's run ends in Hamburg semifinals|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2014/07/19/zverev-run-ends-in-hamburg-semifinals/|website=Fox News|date=19 July 2014}}</ref> and two [[Davis Cup]] ties, against [[Austria]] and [[Argentina]]. By the end of the year, he was ranked No. 170.\n\nIn 2007, he won the first and second professional tournaments of his career: the Casablanca Challenger (in April) and the Rijeka Challenger (in May). In June, at the [[2007 Queen's Club Championships|Queen's Club Championships]], he beat [[Tim Henman]] in the first round after trailing 2\u20134 in the final set, and reached the quarterfinals, where he fell to [[Andy Roddick]]. After that performance, he reached a new career-high ranking of No. 101 on 18 June 2007.\n\nIn the World Group playoffs in the first round of the [[2007 Davis Cup]], \u010cili\u0107 beat [[Benjamin Becker]] of [[Germany]]; however, Croatia went on to lose the tie, three matches to two.<ref name=ndtv1>{{cite web|title=Davis Cup: Germany defeat Croatia 3\u20132|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/tennis/news/4123-davis-cup-germany-defeat-croatia-3-2|website=NDTV Sports|date=22 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n===2008: First ATP singles title===\nIn 2008, \u010cili\u0107 reached the semifinals at the [[Chennai Open]], in both singles and doubles. In the singles, he was defeated by [[Mikhail Youzhny]], who went on to win the tournament. \u010cili\u0107 made it to the fourth round of the [[2008 Australian Open]], taking out two [[Seed (sports)|seed]]s on his way, including [[2007 Australian Open]] finalist [[Fernando Gonz\u00e1lez]]. [[James Blake (tennis)|James Blake]] beat him in the fourth round. He had achieved his goal for the year of reaching the top 40. His fourth-round result at the Australian Open put him at no. 39 in the ATP rankings.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 also made it to the fourth round of [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], beating [[Jarkko Nieminen]] in five sets in the second round and knocking-out 14th seed [[Paul-Henri Mathieu]]. At the 2008 Olympics, he reached the second round of the men's singles, beating [[Juan M\u00f3naco]] before losing to Fernando Gonz\u00e1lez.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ci/marin-cilic-1.html|title=Marin \u010cili\u0107 Bio, Stats, and Results|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> He lost in straight sets to [[Arnaud Cl\u00e9ment]]. At the [[Canada Masters]], he defeated Andy Roddick in reaching the quarterfinal stage, giving his best performance in a Masters Series tournament to date. He lost in three sets to [[Gilles Simon]] in the quarterfinals.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 played the [[Pilot Pen Tennis]] tournament in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], where he won his first ATP title. He defeated [[Viktor Troicki]], [[J\u00fcrgen Melzer]], and [[Igor Andreev]] in early rounds, then 2007 finalist [[Mardy Fish]] in the final. \u010cili\u0107, seeded for the first time at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournament, reached the third round of the US Open, but lost to [[Novak Djokovic]] in a match that lasted almost four hours. \u010cili\u0107 came back from a break down in each of the second, third, and fourth sets. In the first round, he had defeated [[Julien Benneteau]] in five sets in a match that lasted more than four hours, winning the deciding set.\n\n===2009: First Grand Slam quarterfinal===\n\u010cili\u0107 won his first title of 2009 and second career ATP title at the [[2009 Chennai Open|Chennai Open]], defeating first-time finalist [[Somdev Devvarman]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=tennis&id=3825260|title=Cilic wins Chennai Open for 2nd career ATP title|work=sports.espn.go.com|date=11 January 2009|agency=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe reached the fourth round of the [[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Australian Open]] after beating [[David Ferrer]] in straight sets, equalling his 2008 record. In the fourth round, he was defeated by [[Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro]] in four sets.\nLater in the year, \u010cili\u0107 won the [[PBZ Zagreb Indoors]], defeating compatriot [[Mario An\u010di\u0107]] in the final.\nHe helped his country defeat Chilean opponents in the [[Davis Cup]] first-round tie by winning the opening singles match and joining forces with Mario An\u010di\u0107 to win the doubles rubber.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 reached a career best at the [[2009 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]] when he beat 18th seed [[Radek \u0160t\u011bp\u00e1nek]] in the third round in straight sets. After two competitive sets against the third-seeded Andy Murray, \u010cili\u0107 lost the match.<ref name=\"atpworldtour1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Top-Players/Marin-Cilic.aspx?t=pa&y=2009&m=s&e=0#|title=Tennis \u2013 ATP World Tour \u2013 Tennis Players \u2013 Marin \u010cili\u0107|publisher=ATP World Tour|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Marin \u010cili\u0107 at the 2009 Wimbledon Championships 01.jpg|thumb|left|\u010cili\u0107 at the [[2009 Wimbledon Championships]]]]\nHe reached the second round of the [[Queen's Club Championships]], an [[ATP World Tour 250 series]] event, where he was defeated by [[Nicolas Mahut]] of France. He beat [[Alberto Mart\u00edn]] to make it into the second round at Wimbledon and won a five-set match (spread over two days) against Sam Querrey. He played another five-set match in the third round against [[Tommy Haas]]. He recovered from two sets down, but lost 10\u20138 in the deciding set, having held a match point.<ref name=\"atpworldtour1\"/>\n\nDuring the hard-court season, \u010cili\u0107 was defeated in back-to-back events in the first round. At [[Legg Mason Tennis Classic|Washington]], he was defeated in straight sets by [[Somdev Devvarman]]. He then failed to duplicate his quarterfinal appearance in [[Canada Masters|Canada]], losing to [[Mikhail Youzhny]]. In the [[2009 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|US Open]], as the 16th seed, he reached the fourth round, after defeating [[Ryan Sweeting]], [[Jesse Levine]], and [[Denis Istomin]]. He defeated Levine after being down two sets to love, coming back to win. He then scored the biggest upset of the [[2009 US Open (tennis)|2009 US Open]] with a straight-sets victory over second-seeded [[Andy Murray]] in the fourth round. \u010cili\u0107 outclassed Murray by saving all the break points he faced and took advantage of Murray's unforced errors. After the match, he said it was the biggest win of his career to date. However, in the quarterfinals, he lost to the eventual champion [[Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro]], despite leading by one set and an opening break in the second set.<ref name=\"atpworldtour1\"/>\n\nFollowing his impressive US Open run, \u010cili\u0107 participated in the [[2009 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] in [[Beijing]] as the eighth seed. He won his opening match against Russian [[Igor Andreev]], followed by a three-set victory over Frechman [[Julien Benneteau]]. In the quarterfinals he defeated fourth seed [[Nikolay Davydenko]], before stunning world No. 2 and top seed (in the tournament) [[Rafael Nadal]] in a straightforward win. In the final, \u010cili\u0107 went down to second seed [[Novak Djokovi\u0107]] in straight sets.<ref name=\"atpworldtour1\"/>\n\nHe reached the fifth final of his career at the [[2009 Bank Austria-TennisTrophy|Bank Austria Tennis Trophy]] as top seed; however, he lost. He received a wild card for the [[2009 Davidoff Swiss Indoors|Davidoff Swiss Indoors]], where he finished in the quarterfinals, losing to Radek \u0160t\u011bp\u00e1nek. His final tournament of the year was the [[2009 BNP Paribas Masters|BNP Paribas Masters]]. Entered as 12th seed, he came from a set down to defeat [[\u0141ukasz Kubot]] in the second round, and then from a set down again to defeat seventh seed [[Fernando Verdasco]], before coming to a halt in the quarterfinals against eventual finalist [[Ga\u00ebl Monfils]].\n\n===2010: First major semifinal and top 10 ranking===\n\u010cili\u0107 won the [[2010 Chennai Open|Chennai Open]] final, beating [[Stanislas Wawrinka]] of Switzerland in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Top-Players/Marin-Cilic.aspx?t=tf|title=Tennis \u2013 ATP World Tour \u2013 Tennis Players \u2013 Marin Cilic|publisher=ATP World Tour|date=28 September 1988|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.preview.atpworldtour.com/Share/Event-Draws.aspx?e=891&y=2010|title=Tennis \u2013 ATP World Tour \u2013 Draws|publisher=En.preview.atpworldtour.com|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nSeeded 14th at the [[2010 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Australian Open]], he defeated [[Fabrice Santoro]], [[Bernard Tomic]], and [[Stan Wawrinka]] in the first three rounds. In the fourth round, he faced fourth seed and reigning US Open champion [[Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro]]; it was their third meeting in the past five Grand Slams. In a match that lasted more than four and a half hours, \u010cili\u0107 defeated Del Potro to reach his second quarterfinal appearance at a Grand Slam. In the quarterfinals, he defeated seventh seed [[Andy Roddick]] in another five-set victory. In doing so, he became the first Croatian to reach the semifinals at the Australian Open. However, \u010cili\u0107 eventually lost in four sets to Andy Murray, despite winning the first set. \u010cili\u0107 followed up his Australian campaign by defending his title in Zagreb, defeating [[Michael Berrer]] in the final. \u010cili\u0107 achieved a new career-high ranking of No. 9 as a result. \u010cili\u0107 was selected to play singles and doubles partnering with Karlovi\u0107 for the [[Croatia Davis Cup Team]] against [[Ecuador Davis Cup team|Ecuador]] in March 2010. \u010cili\u0107, seeded eighth, lost in the second round to [[Guillermo Garc\u00eda-L\u00f3pez]] at the [[2010 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]].\n\nAt the [[2010 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]], \u010cili\u0107 lost to [[Robin S\u00f6derling]] in the fourth round. \u010cili\u0107 was defeated in the first round of [[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon]] by [[Florian Mayer]].\n\nHe reached the semifinals of the [[Legg Mason Tennis Classic]] in Washington D.C., ending [[Mardy Fish]]'s 11-match winning-streak in the third round. \u010cili\u0107 was defeated by eventual champion David Nalbandian.\n\nAt the [[2010 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|US Open]], \u010cili\u0107 lost to [[Kei Nishikori]] in the second round.\n\n===2011: Sixth ATP title===\n\u010cili\u0107 began the season with a first-round loss to Kei Nishikori in [[2011 Aircel Chennai Open|Chennai]], failing to defend his title. At the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]] he progressed to the fourth round, defeating [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]], [[Santiago Giraldo]], and then [[John Isner]] in a five-set. In the fourth round, he lost to world No. 1, Rafael Nadal. Next, he went to [[Zagreb Open|Zagreb]] to defend another title. Again, he was unable to do so, falling to [[Florian Mayer]] in the quarterfinals.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 played next in [[2011 ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament|Rotterdam]] and lost to [[Viktor Troicki]] in the quarterfinals. He then played in [[2011 Open 13|Marseille]], where he was unseeded. He defeated [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Berdych]] in the quarterfinals and saved one match point in a comeback win against Mikhail Youzhny. He lost to [[Robin S\u00f6derling]] in the final. \u010cili\u0107 played for Croatia in the World Group playoffs in the first round of the [[2011 Davis Cup]], defeating [[Florian Mayer]] in the opening singles rubber. He leveled the tie at 2\u20132 by defeating [[Philipp Kohlschreiber]] in the first reverse singles rubber. However, Germany ultimately won the tie.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 lost in the first round of the [[2011 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]] to [[Rub\u00e9n Ram\u00edrez Hidalgo]] and at [[2011 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon]] to his compatriot [[Ivan Ljubi\u010di\u0107]].\n\nAt Umag, \u010cili\u0107 became the first Croatian man to reach the finals in over 20 years, losing to [[Alexandr Dolgopolov]]. He upset Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro in the second round of the [[Rogers Cup (tennis)|Rogers Cup]] and reached the third round of the US Open, losing to Roger Federer. In ATP 500 in Beijing, he lost the final against world No. 6, [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Berdych]], in three sets. The next week he was upset by [[Albert Ramos]] in the [[Shanghai Rolex Masters]]. He won his sixth career title in Saint Petersburg by defeating world No. 10 [[Janko Tipsarevi\u0107]] in the final. En route to the final, he defeated [[Sergei Bubka (tennis)|Sergei Bubka]], [[Somdev Devvarman]], [[Andreas Seppi]], and Mikhail Youzhny.\n\n===2012: Seventh and eighth ATP titles===\n[[File:Flickr - Carine06 - Marin Cilic (1).jpg|thumb|upright|\u010cili\u0107 during the final of the [[2012 Queen's Club Championships]]]]\n\u010cili\u0107 did not play at the [[2012 Australian Open]], but did play at [[2012 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Indian Wells]], where he lost in the second round to [[David Nalbandian]]. He was defeated by Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro in the third round of [[2012 Sony Ericsson Open|Miami]] and the [[2012 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]]. In June, \u010cili\u0107 won the [[Queen's Club Championships]] in London after his opponent in the final, David Nalbandian, was disqualified in the second set for aggravated behaviour, having kicked the hoarding around a linesman's chair, injuring the linesman.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ornstein|first=David|title=David Nalbandian investigated by police after line judge injury|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/18479244|accessdate=18 June 2012|date=17 June 2012|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn the third round of Wimbledon, he beat [[Sam Querrey]] 7\u20136, 6\u20134, 6\u20137, 6\u20137, 17\u201315 in the second-longest match ever played at Wimbledon in 5 hours and 31 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/18661463|title=Wimbledon 2012: Cilic beats Querrey in second longest match|accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref> He subsequently lost to [[Andy Murray]] in the following round. In July 2012, \u010cili\u0107 became the first home player to win the [[Croatia Open]] after 22 years by defeating [[Marcel Granollers]] of Spain in the final.<ref name=atp101>{{cite web|title=CILIC CRUISES TO FIRST UMAG TROPHY|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/news/tennis/2012/07/28/umag-sunday-cilic-triumphs-over-granollers.aspx|website=atpworldtour.com|date=15 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2012 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]], he reached the second round in the men's singles, beating J\u00fcrgen Melzer before losing to Lleyton Hewitt.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the men's doubles, he reached the quarterfinals with [[Ivan Dodig]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n\u010cili\u0107 was seeded 12th at the [[2012 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], where he matched his 2009 effort in reaching the quarterfinals. He was defeated by the eventual champion Andy Murray despite winning the first set and leading 5\u20131 in the second set.\n\n===2013: Failed drugs test and ban===\n\u010cili\u0107 started his year at the [[Chennai Open]], where he lost to [[Beno\u00eet Paire]] in the quarterfinal. At the [[2013 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Australian Open]], he was seeded 12th but was upset in the third round by Andreas Seppi in a five-set match. In February, \u010cili\u0107 played for Croatia in the [[2013 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]] World Group playoffs against Italy; he defeated [[Paolo Lorenzi]] in the opening singles rubber, and in the first reverse singles, he avenged his earlier loss to Seppi at the Australian Open, prevailing in a straight-sets win. Italy, however, won the tie eventually with a final score of 3\u20132.\n\nAt [[PBZ Zagreb Indoors|Zagreb]], where he had won twice in 2009 and 2010, \u010cili\u0107 won for a third time to earn his ninth career title, defeating [[J\u00fcrgen Melzer]] in the final. \u010cili\u0107 was top seeded in the [[2013 U.S. National Indoor Tennis Championships|Memphis Indoor]] event but lost to [[Kei Nishikori]], the eventual champion, in the quarterfinals. \u010cili\u0107 next played at [[2013 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]], where he lost in the third round to [[Milos Raonic]] in three sets. In the following tournament at [[Sony Open Tennis|Miami]], he defeated world No. 8, [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]], in the fourth round but lost to Andy Murray in the quarterfinals.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 started his clay-court season in [[Monte-Carlo Masters|Monte Carlo]], but lost to [[Richard Gasquet]] in the fourth round. In May, it was announced \u010cili\u0107 had left his longtime coach [[Bob Brett]] and would be coachless at tournaments before hiring a new one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatiaweek.com/marin-cilic-cuts-ties-with-coach-bob-brett/|title=Marin Cilic Cuts Ties With Coach Bob Brett}}</ref> At the [[2013 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]], he lost in the third round to Viktor Troicki in straight sets. In June, \u010cili\u0107 returned to [[Queen's Club Championships|Queen's Club]] to defend his title. He defeated world No. 6, Tomas Berdych, in the quarterfinals, his second top 10 win of the year, and [[Lleyton Hewitt]] in the semifinal. In the final, \u010cili\u0107 lost to Andy Murray in three sets.\n\nAt [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon]] \u010cili\u0107 pulled out before his second round match claiming he had a left knee injury where he was scheduled to play [[Kenny de Schepper]] of France.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/tennis/news/12110/8793574/Wimbledon-Steve-Darcis-and-Marin-Cilic-forced-out-through-injury | title=Wimbledon: Steve Darcis and Marin Cilic forced out through injury|work=Sky Sports}}</ref> However, a month later it was revealed that \u010cili\u0107 had pulled out due to failing a drugs test in Munich, allegedly{{clarify|alleged by who?|date=March 2018}} for \"incautious use of glucose.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/226079.html | title=Marin Cilic investigated over 'failed drugs test'| publisher=ESPN |website=www.espn.co.uk | date=30 July 2013}}</ref> On 16 September 2013, he received a backdated nine-month ban due to testing positive for the banned substance [[nikethamide]]. \u010cili\u0107 claimed that the banned substance was ingested via Coramine glucose tablets bought at a pharmacy by a member of his team, and as a result the independent tribunal believed that he did not intend to enhance his performance. The suspension ran until 1 February 2014 and all prize money and points since the positive test including the Munich tournament were null and forfeited.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marin Cilic: Croatian banned for nine months|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/24116444|work=BBC Sport|date=17 September 2013}}</ref> \u010cili\u0107 appealed against this ban to the Court of Arbitration for Sport, who reduced the ban from nine months to four months on 25 October. They stated that \"the degree of fault committed by the athlete was inferior to that established in the (tribunal) decision and the sanction imposed was too severe in view of the degree of fault\". \u010cili\u0107, whose ranking had dropped to number 47, received an immediate boost as results at the French Open, Queen's and Wimbledon were reinstated.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/10404579/Marin-Cilic-has-doping-ban-reduced-to-four-months-by-Court-of-Arbitration-for-Sport.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Marin Cilic has doping ban reduced to four months by Court of Arbitration for Sport | date=25 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marin Cilic's drugs ban reduced following appeal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/24672616|work=BBC Sport|date=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2013, \u010cili\u0107 started working with [[Goran Ivani\u0161evi\u0107]] as his new coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2014/02/9/Cilic-Ivanisevic-Improvement.aspx|title=News \u2013 ATP World Tour \u2013 Tennis}}</ref>\n\n===2014: US Open champion===\n{{Main|2014 Marin \u010cili\u0107 tennis season}}\n[[File:Cilic MA14 (16) - Copy (14239610239).jpg|thumb|upright|\u010cili\u0107 at the [[2014 Madrid Open]]]]\n\u010cili\u0107 returned to the tour at [[Brisbane International|Brisbane]]. He defeated [[Denis Istomin]] and [[Grigor Dimitrov]] to reach the quarterfinal, where he lost to Kei Nishikori. In [[2014 Apia International Sydney|Sydney]], he lost to Denis Istomin in the second round. At the [[2014 Australian Open|Australian Open]] second round, \u010cili\u0107 lost to [[Gilles Simon]] in five sets.\n\nIn February, \u010cili\u0107 successfully defended his title at [[2014 PBZ Zagreb Indoors|Zagreb]] without dropping a set, winning his 10th career title. \u010cili\u0107 extended his winning streak at the [[2014 ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament|Rotterdam Open]]. He defeated [[Lukas Rosol]], world No. 10, Jo-Wilfried Tsonga, world No. 6, Andy Murray and [[Igor Sijsling]], reaching the second final of the season, where he lost to Tomas Berdych. \u010cili\u0107 continued his excellent form in [[Delray Beach International Tennis Championships|Delray Beach]], reaching his third consecutive final of the season, where he defeated [[Kevin Anderson (tennis)|Kevin Anderson]] and won his 11th singles title.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 reached the fourth round of the [[2014 Indian Wells Masters|Indian Wells Masters]]. He defeated [[Paolo Lorenzi]] and [[Tommy Robredo]] to set up a clash with Novak Djokovic. However, he lost the match in three sets. His good form came to an end in the [[2014 Miami Masters|Miami Masters]] where he lost to [[\u00c9douard Roger-Vasselin]] in the second round.\n\nDuring the clay season, \u010cili\u0107 reached the quarterfinals in [[2014 Barcelona Open Banc Sabadell|Barcelona]]. He lost in early rounds in both [[2014 Mutua Madrid Open|Madrid Open]] and [[2014 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Rome Masters]]. At the [[2014 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]], \u010cili\u0107 reached the third round before losing to Djokovic in four sets.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 returned to [[2014 Aegon Championships|Queen's Club]] in June, where he was last year's runner-up on the grass court, however he was knocked out by [[Marinko Matosevic]] in the first round. \u010cili\u0107 successfully rebounded at [[2014 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], reached the quarterfinals for the first time, beating [[Paul-Henri Mathieu]], [[Andreas Haider-Maurer]], Tomas Berdych and [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my Chardy]] before losing to eventual champion Novak Djokovic in five sets.\n\nIn July, \u010cili\u0107 played [[2014 ATP Vegeta Croatia Open Umag|Croatia Open]] on home soil, where he was defeated in the semifinals by Tommy Robredo. In the warmup [[US Open Series]], \u010cili\u0107 advanced to the third round at [[2014 Rogers Cup \u2013 Men's Singles|Rogers Cup]], where he lost to Roger Federer in a close three-set match. In the following [[2014 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati Masters]], \u010cili\u0107 also reached the third round before losing to Stan Wawrinka.\n\nSeeded 14th at the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], \u010cili\u0107 defeated [[Marcos Baghdatis]], [[Illya Marchenko]] and Kevin Anderson to set up a fourth-round fixture against Gilles Simon, beating the Frenchman for the first time in five matches. He then went on to defeat both world No. 7, Tomas Berdych, and world No. 3, Roger Federer, in straight sets to reach his maiden Grand Slam final. This was also his first ever victory against Federer in all competitions. \u010cili\u0107 defeated 10th seed Kei Nishikori in straight sets in the final, claiming his first Grand Slam title and becoming the first Croatian to win a men's Grand Slam event since his coach [[Goran Ivani\u0161evi\u0107]] won the [[2001 Wimbledon Championships]].<ref name=bbc1>{{cite web|last1=Newbery|first1=Piers|title=Marin Cilic wins 2014 US Open and first Grand Slam title|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/tennis/29120117|website=bbc.com|date=8 September 2014}}</ref> His triumph in the final was also his 300th professional victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/sep/09/marin-cilic-kei-nishikori-us-open-final-2014|title=Marin Cilic crushes Kei Nishikori to win US Open and first grand slam|first=Kevin|last=Mitchell|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 September 2014|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his US Open victory, \u010cili\u0107 played for Croatia in [[2014 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]] World Group playoffs against Netherlands. Initially signed up for doubles rubber only, \u010cili\u0107 and teammate [[Marin Draganja]] beat [[Robin Haase]] and [[Jean-Julien Rojer]]. After a 2:2 tie between two countries, however, \u010cili\u0107 stepped up and played the deciding fifth singles rubber in place of young compatriot [[Borna \u0106ori\u0107]], where he defeated [[Thiemo de Bakker]]. The victory earned Croatia the World Group status for 2015.\n\nAt [[2014 China Open (tennis)|China Open]], \u010cili\u0107 advanced to the quarterfinal before losing to Andy Murray. In [[2014 Shanghai Rolex Masters|Shanghai Masters]], \u010cili\u0107 was upset in the first round by fellow countryman [[Ivo Karlovi\u0107]] after losing the tiebreak in the third set. \u010cili\u0107, however, rebounded at [[2014 Kremlin Cup|Kremlin Cup]], where he defeated [[Roberto Bautista Agut]] in the final and won his fourth title of the season. On 18 October, it was announced \u010cili\u0107, as the then reigning US Open champion, had become the fifth player (after Djokovic, Nadal, Federer and Wawrinka) to qualify for the [[2014 ATP World Tour Finals|ATP World Tour Finals]] in London from 9\u201316 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.barclaysatpworldtourfinals.com/en/news-and-media/tennis/finals-2014-cilic-qualifies|title=Cilic to Make Debut|work=Barclays ATP World Tour Finals|date=18 October 2014}}</ref> \u010cili\u0107 subsequently withdrew from the [[2014 Valencia Open 500|Valencia Open]] and [[2014 BNP Paribas Masters|Paris Masters]] in order to allow time for an arm injury to heal before the tour finals.  He ultimately lost all three matches in the round robin.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 finished the season as world No. 9 in year-end ATP rankings.\n\n===2015: 14th ATP title===\nA shoulder injury prevented \u010cili\u0107 from playing the [[Brisbane International]] and [[2015 Australian Open|Australian Open]].\n\nAfter being sidelined for more than two months, \u010cili\u0107 made his season debut at the [[2015 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells Masters]]. After receiving a bye in the first round, he lost in the second round to [[Juan M\u00f3naco]] in straight sets. \u010cili\u0107 subsequently withdrew from the [[2015 Miami Open|Miami Open]] due to the shoulder problem. \u010cili\u0107 returned to tour at [[2015 Monte-Carlo Rolex Masters|Monte-Carlo Masters]], where he advanced to quarterfinals, before losing to eventual champion Novak Djokovic.\n\nAt the 2015 French Open, \u010cili\u0107 lost to David Ferrer in the fourth round in straight sets. At [[Queen's Club]], \u010cili\u0107 was beaten in the second round by [[Victor Troicki]] in three sets. \u010cili\u0107 matched his 2014 Wimbledon performance, reaching the quarterfinals again after eliminating [[Hiroki Moriya|Moriya]], [[Ri\u010dardas Berankis|Berankis]], [[John Isner|Isner]] (12\u201310 in the fifth set), and [[Denis Kudla|Kudla]].\n\n\u010cili\u0107 returned to Flushing Meadows for the [[2015 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] to defend his title, reaching the semi finals where he was beaten in straight sets by [[Novak Djokovic]] who also went on to win in the final. \u010cili\u0107 managed to defend his title at the [[2015 Kremlin Cup|Kremlin Cup]], winning the final in almost identical fashion to the previous year. In the final, he defeated the same player as the previous year, Roberto Bautista Agut, by the same scoreline, 6\u20134, 6\u20134.\n\n===2016: First Masters title and Davis Cup final===\nIn the first major of the year, Marin \u010cili\u0107 was seeded 12th, but he was upset by Bautista Agut in the third round of the Australian Open.\n\nAt Indian Wells, he reached the quarterfinals before losing to No. 15 seed David Goffin. At the Miami Masters, he was defeated by Gilles Simon in third round.\n\nAt the [[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon Championships]], \u010cili\u0107 repeated his efforts of the previous two years making the quarterfinals, after eliminating rival Kei Nishikori in the fourth round. In the quarterfinals, he met third seed Roger Federer; \u010cili\u0107 won the first two sets and had match points in the fourth set but was unable to convert eventually being eliminated in five sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/articles/2016-07-06/federer_conjures_up_great_escape.html |title=Wimbledon 2016 |publisher=wimbledon.com |accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Olympics]], he competed in the men's singles and the men's doubles with [[Marin Draganja]]. He reached the last 16 in the singles and the second round in the doubles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/rio-2016/results/sports/tennis/mens-singles|title=Results \u2013 Mens Singles \u2013 Tennis \u2013 Rio 2016 \u2013 Olympics|website=BBC Sport|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/rio-2016/results/sports/tennis/mens-doubles|title=Results \u2013 Mens Doubles \u2013 Tennis \u2013 Rio 2016 \u2013 Olympics|website=BBC Sport|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, \u010cili\u0107 announced his new coach as [[Jonas Bj\u00f6rkman]] in a video posted to MyATP. In [[2016 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati]], \u010cili\u0107 claimed his maiden Masters title, defeating Andy Murray in the final in straight sets. This win ended Murray's 22-match winning streak, dating back to 2016 Queen's Club. The Croat beat Viktor Troicki, [[Fernando Verdasco]], Tom\u00e1\u0161 Berdych, [[Borna \u0106ori\u0107]] and Grigor Dimitrov in the route to the final. \u010cili\u0107 returned to the top 10 in the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://live-tennis.eu |title=Live ATP Rankings |publisher=live-tennis.eu |accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October, he captured his maiden ATP 500 level title at the [[2016 Swiss Indoors|Swiss Indoors]], beating Nishikori in straight sets in the final. At the [[2016 Paris Masters|Paris Masters]], \u010cili\u0107 defeated Djokovic for the first time in his career to reach the semifinals, where he subsequently lost to John Isner. His run guaranteed that he would qualify for the [[ATP World Tour Finals]] for the second time in three years. There, in the round robin, he lost to Murray and Wawrinka, but defeated Nishikori for his first-ever win at the Finals. With this victory, he rose to No. 6 in the ATP rankings.\n\nIn the final of the [[2016 Davis Cup World Group|Davis Cup]], with Croatia leading Argentina by 2\u20131 in matches, \u010cili\u0107 led [[Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro]] by two sets to love needing one more set to win the title for his country. However, del Potro went on to win the match in five sets and Argentina won the deciding match to win the tournament.\n\n===2017: Wimbledon final===\n\u010cili\u0107 started his 2017 season as first seed at the [[2017 Aircel Chennai Open \u2013 Singles|Chennai Open]] but lost to [[Jozef Koval\u00edk]] in the second round. In the first major of the year, the [[2017 Australian Open|Australian Open]], \u010cili\u0107 lost in the second round to [[Dan Evans (tennis)|Dan Evans]].\n\nIn February, he lost in his opening match in [[2017 Open Sud de France \u2013 Singles|Montpellier]], reached the quarterfinals of the [[2017 ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament \u2013 Singles|Rotterdam]], and the semifinals of [[2017 Abierto Mexicano Telcel \u2013 Men's Singles|Acapulco]].\n\n\u010cili\u0107 was eliminated in the second rounds of [[2017 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Indian Wells]], [[2017 Miami Open|Miami Open]], and [[2017 Mutua Madrid Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Madrid Open]], but reached the quarterfinals in [[2017 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Rome]], and [[2017 Monte-Carlo Rolex Masters \u2013 Singles|Monte-Carlo]]. In May, \u010cili\u0107 won the title at the [[2017 Istanbul Open \u2013 Singles|Istanbul Open]], defeating Milos Raonic in the final, in straight sets. This was his 14th ATP 250 title, second clay title, and 17th title overall. Additionally, \u010cili\u0107's victory in Istanbul meant that 2017 was his tenth consecutive year winning at least one ATP title.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 reached the quarterfinal of the [[2017 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]] for the first time in his career and thus became one of the few tennis players who reached the quarterfinal stage of every Grand Slam championship.\n\nIn June, at the Queen's Club Championships, Marin made the final for the third time in his career. There he faced [[Feliciano L\u00f3pez]], losing in three sets, after having a championship point in the final-set tiebreaker. At [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], \u010cili\u0107 reached the quarterfinals without dropping a set. There, he defeated Gilles M\u00fcller in five sets to reach his first Wimbledon semifinal. In the semifinal he recovered from a one set deficit to defeat Sam Querrey in four sets. In the final he was defeated by Roger Federer in straight sets, he struggled with a blister.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2017/jul/16/wimbledon-2017-roger-federer-v-marin-cilic-in-mens-singles-final-live|title= Wimbledon 2017: Roger Federer beats Marin Cilic to seal record eighth title \u2013 as it happened|date=16 July 2017|work=Guardian|accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn adductor injury forced \u010cili\u0107 to miss the Montreal and Cincinnati Masters events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2017/08/03/murray-cilic-withdraw-from-rogers-cup-in-montreal|title=Murray, Cilic withdraw from Rogers Cup in Montreal|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> \u010cili\u0107 returned to play at the [[2017 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] where he lost to [[Diego Schwartzman]] in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-us-open-notes-20170901-story.html|title=U.S. Open: Diego Schwartzman enjoys his stature after upset of Marin Cilic|first=Helene|last=Elliott|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> Despite this, following the tournament's conclusion \u010cili\u0107 broke into the top five for the first time in his career.\n\nIn October, \u010cili\u0107 reached the semifinals of the [[2017 Rakuten Japan Open Tennis Championships \u2013 Singles|Tokyo]], [[2017 Shanghai Rolex Masters \u2013 Singles|Shanghai]], [[2017 Swiss Indoors \u2013 Singles|Basel]], and the quarterfinals of the [[2017 Rolex Paris Masters \u2013 Singles|Paris Masters]]. \u010cili\u0107 failed to win a match in the [[2017 ATP Finals|ATP Finals]] despite going to three sets against Federer, [[Alexander Zverev]], and [[Jack Sock]]. \u010cili\u0107 finished the season as world No. 6 for the second consecutive year.\n\n===2018: Third Grand Slam final, Davis Cup champion, and world No. 3===\n\u010cili\u0107 started his 2018 season as first seed in [[2018 Maharashtra Open \u2013 Singles|Pune, India]]. He lost in semifinals to eventual champion Gilles Simon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Simon Rolls Back The Years in Pune|url=https://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/cilic-anderson-pune-2018-friday|website=atpworldtour.com|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite mixed form since his Wimbledon campaign, \u010cili\u0107 defeated world No. 1, [[Rafael Nadal]], at the [[2018 Australian Open|Australian Open]] after the Spaniard retired hurt in the fifth set, going on to reach another Grand-Slam final against Federer. This made him the first Croatian to ever reach the singles final at Melbourne Park. He eventually lost in five sets. The match garnered minor criticism from some tennis pundits for being played indoors to favour Federer, despite the Australian Open traditionally being an outdoor event. \u010cili\u0107 later admitted that he found it difficult to adjust to the changed conditions. However, it remained disputed that who among the two players was going to be favored in indoor conditions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Controversial decision in Australian Open final divides tennis world|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/tennis/australian-open/controversial-decision-in-australian-open-final-divides-tennis-world/news-story/ba6cabafdd3fd772f7547cc9ee2d708d|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref> At the conclusion of the tournament, \u010cili\u0107 reached a career-high ATP ranking of No. 3. He remained at that position for 12 weeks, before being surpassed by [[Alexander Zverev Jr.|Alexander Zverev]]. \n[[Image:Marin \u010cili\u0107, finale Coupe Davis 2018.jpg|thumb|280px|right|\u010cili\u0107 after victory vs Jo-Wilfried Tsonga, [[2018 Davis Cup]], final]]\nIn the first two [[Masters 1000]] events of the season \u010cili\u0107 was defeated by [[Philipp Kohlschreiber]] (at [[2018 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]], in the round of 32) and John Isner, the eventual champion of [[2018 Miami Open|Miami]]. In the clay-court season, \u010cili\u0107 played four tournaments reaching the quarterfinals of [[2018 Monte-Carlo Masters|Monte Carlo]], the semifinals of [[2018 Italian Open|Rome]], and the quarterfinals at the [[2018 French Open|French Open]]. \u010cili\u0107 failed to defend his only title from the 2017 season at [[2018 Istanbul Open \u2013 Singles|Istanbul]], losing in his opening match to [[Malek Jaziri]]. This defeat marked the first time since February 2014 that \u010cili\u0107 had not held any tournament on the ATP Tour.\n\nAt [[2018 Queen's Club Championships|Queen's Club]], \u010cili\u0107 was the top seed. He reached the final, where he contested a close match with Djokovic, coming out on top in three sets saving match point in the process to claim his second title at Queen's Club and second career win over Djokovic. At [[2018 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], he was drawn in the top half and was considered one of the biggest threats to Roger Federer's title defense. He was upset in the second round by [[Guido Pella]] in five sets, after comfortably winning the first two sets.\n\nDuring the North American summer hard-court swing, \u010cili\u0107 made strong showings in [[2018 Rogers Cup|Toronto]] and [[2018 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati]], losing in both tournaments to the eventual champion in tight three setters (Rafael Nadal in Toronto and Novak Djokovic in Cincinnati). At the [[2018 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], \u010cili\u0107 recovered from a two set deficit to defeat teenager [[Alex de Minaur]] in the third round. \u010cili\u0107 eventually lost in the quarterfinals against Kei Nishikori in a replay of the [[2014 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2014 final]].\n\n\u010cili\u0107 helped Croatia reach the [[2018 Davis Cup World Group|Davis Cup finals]] for the second time in three years, winning one of his two singles rubbers against the [[United States Davis Cup team|USA]]. In October, \u010cili\u0107 suffered a string of early exits at [[2018 Rakuten Japan Open Tennis Championships \u2013 Singles|Tokyo]], [[2018 Shanghai Rolex Masters \u2013 Singles|Shanghai]], and [[2018 Swiss Indoors \u2013 Singles|Basel]]. He rebounded from this trough in form at the [[2018 Rolex Paris Masters \u2013 Singles|Paris Masters]] reaching the quarterfinals for a third consecutive year before losing to Djokovic in three sets. By winning a set he ended the Serb's streak of 30 consecutive sets won.<ref>{{cite web|title=Novak Stretched, But Battles To 21st Straight Win|url=https://www.atpworldtour.com/en/news/djokovic-cilic-paris-2018-friday|website=atpworldtour.com|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n\u010cili\u0107 qualified for the [[2018 ATP Finals|Tour Finals]] for a third successive time and fourth time overall. His disappointing record at the event continued winning only one of his three round-robin matches, bringing his overall record at the event to {{tennis record|won=2|lost=10}}.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 led the [[Croatia Davis Cup team|Croatian national team]] at the [[2018 Davis Cup World Group#France vs. Croatia|2018 Davis Cup final]] against [[France Davis Cup team|France]] on the clay courts of [[Lille]]. After comfortably defeating Tsonga in his first match, \u010cili\u0107 found himself in the same position he was in the [[2016 Davis Cup World Group#Croatia vs. Argentina|2016 final]], having to win his second rubber to guarantee Croatia the title. This time however, \u010cili\u0107 defeated his opponent, [[Lucas Pouille]], in straight sets to grab the decisive victory for Croatia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Davis Cup final: Marin Cilic beats Lucas Pouille as Croatia claim title|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/tennis/46336884|website=bbc.com|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019: Struggles with form, fall from top 20===\n\u010cili\u0107 started his year at [[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Australian Open]]. In his third round match against Fernando Verdasco, \u010cili\u0107 saved two match points and came back from a two set deficit to advance to the fourth round. This was the seventh time in \u010cili\u0107's career that he had won a match after being down two sets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cilic Escapes in Comeback Win, Plays Bautista Agut in Last 16|url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/cilic-verdasco-bautista-agut-australian-open-2019-friday|website=ATP Tour|accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> In the fourth round, \u010cili\u0107 was upset by an in-form Roberto Bautista Agut.\n\nOver his next three tournaments, \u010cili\u0107 only managed to win one match, while being eliminated early at [[2019 Dubai Tennis Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Dubai]], [[2019 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Indian Wells]], and [[2019 Miami Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Miami]]. As a result of his poor form in the early hard court season, \u010cili\u0107 fell from the worlds top ten for the first time in over two years.\n\nAfter another two winless tournaments to start the clay court season (at [[2019 Monte-Carlo Masters \u2013 Singles|Monte-Carlo]] and [[2019 Hungarian Open \u2013 Singles|Budapest]]), \u010cili\u0107 finally broke his slump at the [[2019 Mutua Madrid Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Madrid Masters]] by winning three consecutive matches against [[Martin Kli\u017ean]], [[Jan-Lennard Struff]], & [[Laslo \u0110ere]] on the way to the quarterfinals. However, he had to withdraw before his match against Djokovic due to food poisoning. By reaching the quarterfinals, \u010cili\u0107 became one of the few players on the Tour to reach the quarterfinal stage of all [[ATP Tour Masters 1000|nine Masters 1000]] tournaments. \u010cili\u0107 lost his second round match at both [[2019 Italian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Rome]] and the [[2019 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|French Open]], to Jan-Lennard Struff and Grigor Dimitrov respectively.\n\n\u010cili\u0107 failed to defend his [[2019 Queen's Club Championships \u2013 Singles|Queen's Club]] title, leaving the Croat out of the worlds top 15 for the first time in five years. This also marked the first time since August 2008 that \u010cili\u0107 had not reached a tournament final in over a year. \u010cili\u0107 lost in the second round of [[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon]] to [[Jo\u00e3o Sousa]] in straight sets.\n\nIn the North American summer hard-court season, \u010cili\u0107 competed in [[2019 Citi Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Washington]], [[2019 Rogers Cup \u2013 Men's Singles|Montreal]], [[2019 Western & Southern Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Cincinnati]], and the [[2019 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|US Open]] in New York. \u010cili\u0107 fell from the worlds top 20 after failing to match his previous year's performance at the first three events. At the US Open \u010cili\u0107 reached the fourth round where he showed improvements to form during a four set loss against eventual champion Nadal.\n\n==Clothing and equipment==\nAs of 2018 \u010cili\u0107 plays with the Head YouTek Radical MidPlus with a custom drilled 16x19 string pattern, painted to look like the Head Graphene Touch Prestige Mid. For strings he uses a hybrid of Babolat VS Touch mains and Luxilon ALU Power crosses. He wore [[Fila (company)|Fila]] apparel until the 2011 season, when he got a 5-year contract with [[Li-Ning]], switching back to [[Fila (company)|Fila]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tennisconnected.com/home/2011/01/04/cilic-switches-to-li-ning-apparel-and-shoes/|title=Cilic Switches to Li-Ning Apparel and Shoes|date=4 January 2011|work=tennisconnected.com|accessdate=20 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223025540/http://tennisconnected.com/home/2011/01/04/cilic-switches-to-li-ning-apparel-and-shoes/|archivedate=23 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Main|Marin \u010cili\u0107 career statistics}}\n\n===Grand Slam singles performance timeline===\n{{Performance key|short=yes}}\n''Current through the [[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2020 Australian Open]].''\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;font-size:96%\n|-\n!Tournament!![[2006 ATP Tour|2006]]!![[2007 ATP Tour|2007]]!![[2008 ATP Tour|2008]]!![[2009 ATP World Tour|2009]]!![[2010 ATP World Tour|2010]]!![[2011 ATP World Tour|2011]]!![[2012 ATP World Tour|2012]]!![[2013 ATP World Tour|2013]]!![[2014 ATP World Tour|2014]]!![[2015 ATP World Tour|2015]]!![[2016 ATP World Tour|2016]]!![[2017 ATP World Tour|2017]]!![[2018 ATP World Tour|2018]]!![[2019 ATP World Tour|2019]]!![[2020 ATP World Tour|2020]]!!SR!!W\u2013L!!Win%\n|-\n|align=left| [[Australian Open]]\n|A\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2007 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|4R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2010 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|SF]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2011 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|4R]]\n|A\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2013 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|3R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2014 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2R]]\n|A\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2016 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|3R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2017 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2R]]\n|bgcolor=thistle|[[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|F]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|4R]]\n|bgcolor=afeeee|[[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|4R]]\n|0 / 12\n|32\u201312\n|72%\n|-\n|align=left| [[French Ope